Arthur Jones the Nautilus inventor wrote how when he was young and travelling aimlessly between small towns looking for adventure or odd jobs random young women would just walk up to him and ask to come with him. Just offered themselves. Total loyalty. Total faith in him.

That was during the Great Depression. They were girls from good families, not in poverty, chaste, beautiful, but wanted out regardless of circumstances. Just approached and asked to come with him, said they were ready to take their clothes in a suitcase and leave the same night.

He always refused because he didn't want to put them in danger sleeping near highways in the rain, eating scraps, sharing company with vagabonds and criminals,  etc. but then regretted not taking this or that particular girl with himself, always wondered what it could have been.
